 to inspire generations of Chinese readers.With this long-awaited translation, English-language readers can immerse themselves in the invention and satirical wit of one of the world's great literary cosmopolitans. This collection brings together Qian's best short works, combining his iconoclastic essays on the "book of life" from Written in the Margins of Life (1941) with the four masterful short stories of Human, Beast, Ghost (1946). His essays elucidate substantive issues through deceptively simple subjects-the significance of windows versus doors, for example, or the blind spots of literary criticsand assert the primacy of critical and creative independence. His stories blur the boundaries between humans, beasts, and ghosts as they struggle through life, death, and resurrection. Christopher G. Rea situates these works within China's wartime politics and Qian's literary vision, highlighting significant changes that Qian Zhongshu made to different editions of his writings and providing unprecedented insight into the author's creative process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChinese essaysvTranslations into English. 0aShort stories, ChinesevTranslations into English. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh1 aHu, Dennis.1 aMao, Nathan.1 aMao, Yiran.1 aRea, Christopher G.1 aRea, Christopher G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWilliams, Philip.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/qian1527440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231526548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231526548.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia Univers